To the search committee¶

As a preface, I wanted to give an outline of where I would see this computational exercise fitting into the context of a full course. Whether in a generic data analysis course or in a course specifically geared to bioinformatics, there are a number of foundational skills that I would expect students to be familiar with prior to delving into a full dataset such as this one. Below I list, with links, content I would have introduced the students to prior to this exercise:

  • JupyterLab for running and editing ipython notebooks
  • Data frames as a way to read, write, and manipulate datasets, specifically with the Pandas library in Python
  • The concept of tidy data as a convenient way to organize data prior to analysis
  • Exploratory Data Analysis, emphasizing the value of looking at your data before just jumping into the analysis
  • Data visualization choices with Bokeh and Holoviews. Here, the plotting libraries used matter less than thinking critically about how we plot our data
  • Understanding how p-values are computed and null hypothesis significance tests

Throughout, the blue text highlights where students would be asked to engage, whether through discussion or computation. The black text would be more or less what I would post online after the exercise.

Lesson plan¶

Learning objectives¶

These are explicitly included in the exercise below, as I think it's important to be transparent with students as to why you are having them do a certain exercise.

Assessment¶

Formative assessment The hands-on nature of this exercise lends itself well to in-the-moment feedback. Especially during the large, computational time slot, I (and TAs if possible) would be filtering around the room to see how students are doing and help clear up any misconceptions.

Summative assessment The end of this exercise purposefully transitions to a more open-ended question, that I would imagine students completing on their own time as a homework problem. My preference would be to not have any aspect of in-class activity itself be graded so as to lower the pressure for students to perform under a time constraint. Rather, I would like to give students the time they need to wrangle with the ideas outside of the classroom before submitting a document to be graded.

Timeline¶

I imagine each question period to take around 5 mins, for students to discuss among themselves and then regroup to have a few groups share their thoughts.

The exploratory data analysis will be the bluk of the exercise, and I can imagine it take up to half of the entire time. I see this time as really getting the students familiar with the a nature of the dataset, preparing them to tackle the full problem at the end.

Finally, the final project pitched to them is intentionally open-ended and would transition well into a homework assignment. Having this structure means that all students, regardless of background, would be able to be engaged the whole time. That is, more advanced students wouldn't just be sitting around waiting for everyone else to finish, but also less advanced students wouldn't feel pressured to get to a specific result by the end of the session.

Modalities¶

As illustrated above, I would have students answer questions and report back, as well as spend a substantial chunk of time just working on their computers with the data. I would have students working in small groups (of 3 or 4) since science (and thus data analysis) is rarely done in isolation. This format I think well emulates the process of scientific discovery, where people are often bouncing ideas off of one another.

Misconceptions¶

  • In my experience, students (myself at first as well) often struggle with Pandas syntax, as it can be a bit more clunky or verbose than indexing arrays, for example. As I mention below, I just try to assure student that looking things up is 100% okay, and to just refer to previous examples if possible.

  • Inquisitive students may take issue with the gene names in the ferret data set, since they are given serial number identifiers rather than common gene names. Similarly, students my take issue with the gene names in the paper not matching the gene names in the dataset (IFN-1 vs. IFNA1, for example). I purposely don't draw attention to this since I want students to come across these very real wrinkles that come up when working with "real" data.

  • Depending on the student's comfort with the concept of "tidy data", they may disagree that the tidy dataset is actually more useful as it sacrifices human readability in favor of computer readability. I would encourage them to try to make comparable plots with the original vs. the tidy dataframe to illustrate how much easier it is to access the information you care about when the data are tidy.

Resources¶

  • As I mentioned in the beginning, such an exercise would likely appear partway through a course. If students are having some issues with syntax or other coding-related issues, I could point them to the pre-existing materials (like those shown above) as as reminder.

  • Also for me, I like to emphasize that for coding, Google is your best friend. For students that feel bad that they don't "know" something immediately, I would probably reassure them that I had to Google many things even when making this exercise.

  • Lastly, working in groups can help students clarify misconception amongst themselves. Every person will have their own strengths to bring to the table, and they can bounce ideas off of each other. Additionally, if I see one group is stuck a point that another group just wrangled with, I can have them share their insight. Having to explain your solution to another group helps solidify your own understanding, while also building camaraderie with your classmates.

  • And as a "cheating" fourth resource, I (and my TAs if I have them) are of course a resource for student while they work on their exercises.

In-Class Exercise¶

Learning objectives¶

  • Creation of illustrative data visualizations
  • Application of hypothesis testing to differential gene expression

Introduction to the paper¶

For this exercise, we will be working with data from a recent paper by Blanco-Melo et al. regarding the transcriptional response of cells to SARS-CoV-2 relative to other respiratory viruses. There primary conclusions are illustrated in their graphical abstract included below:

For our exercise, we will primarily be focusing on the bottom part of the abstract, where they illustrate the most note-worthy differences in gene expression between COVID and other respiratory viruses, with the size of the arrows corresponding to the level of expression. In words, they describe their primary results as:

Here we offer an in-depth analysis of the transcriptional response to SARS-CoV-2 compared with other respiratory viruses. Cell and animal models of SARS-CoV-2 infection, in addition to transcriptional and serum profiling of COVID-19 patients, consistently revealed a unique and inappropriate inflammatory response. This response is defined by low levels of type I and III interferons juxtaposed to elevated chemokines and high expression of IL-6. We propose that reduced innate antiviral defenses coupled with exuberant inflammatory cytokine production are the defining and driving features of COVID-19.

Question: Before delving into the data, what experimental approaches would you use to address the primary question of the paper? What techniques would you use if you were interested in the expression of all genes? What about if you were interested in following up with a handful of specific genes? ¶

For this we will be using the Pandas library, as it provides a number of useful functions for manipulating and analyzing data structures. For this exercise, we will be looking at the human dataset, but feel free to play around with the ferret dataset as well. Note that df.head() means we only display the first 5 rows of the dataset, so as to not overwhelm our browser, but the full dataset is in fact saved in memory.

Question: Is this data tidy, why or why not? How might you restructure it? What would your columns be in your tidied dataframe? ¶

At this point, students will spend a few minutes in group discussing why this data isn't tidy (i.e. each row doesn't correspond to an individual measurement/observation) and discuss how they would go about making it tidy. In the interest of time, I am providing a pre-tidied version of the data for the students to continue working with for the remainder of the exercise, but they should be able to do this as well. (The code for tidying the data is included in tidying.html in this folder.)

The value of having our data organized this way will become much more apparent as we begin to plot, but we can see that each row is in fact a single observation, and we have broken out the information previously contained in the treatment name into it's constituent parts: treatment type, series number, and replicate number. This organization will make it much easier to grab all the data of a given treatment type, without have to determine how many technical and biological replicates were done.

Activity: Exploratory data analysis¶

Take the next 20 minutes or so to explore the data on a gene by gene basis, specifically paying attention to the genes the authors highlight in their graphical abstract. Can you validate some of the primary claims of the paper? Are there other comparisons you are interested examining? When comparing gene expression across two treatment types, think carefully about the type of data visualization you choose, and be able to discuss why you chose the plot type you did.

As a way to get started, it might be worthwhile to review all the treatment conditions that are contained in this dataset, printed with each item on a new line for ease of reading.

For ease of exploration, I wrote a function that will plot the counts as a strip plot for a given gene and list of treatment types. I expect students would take a more manual approach, which is fine as well.

In [5]:
def treatment_comp_plot(df, gene, treatments):
    """
    trims the dataframe for the given gene and list of treatments provided
    plots the resultiing categorical plots as a strip plot
    """
    
    # trim only the gene of interest
    df_trimmed = df.loc[df['gene']==gene]
    
    # intialize boolean array for treatments to keep
    bool_array = np.zeros(len(df_trimmed), dtype=bool)
    
    # loop through treatments and note those in our treatment list of interest
    for i, treatment in enumerate(df_trimmed["treatment"]):
        if treatment in treatments:
            bool_array[i] = True
    
    # trim the dataframe by the treatment boolean array
    df_trimmed = df_trimmed.loc[bool_array]
    
    # plotting
    p = hv.Scatter(
    data=df_trimmed,
    kdims=['treatment'],
    vdims=['count'],
    label=gene
    ).opts(
        jitter=0.1,
        tools=['hover'],
        xrotation=45,
        size=5
    )
    
    return p

As just one example of many possible plots, below I show the counts for INF-1 (named IFNA1) for NHBE cells infected with a mock treatment, SARS-CoV-2, and IAV (a common respiratory virus). From just a quick glance, we can validate what is seen in the graphical abstract, where the COVID-infected cells fail to express INF-1 to the same degree as cells infected by other respiratory viruses.

Regroup ¶

At this point I would take some time to have a handful of groups each take turns sharing one exemplary plot that they made during their exploration. This will give students the opportunity to see other plotting choices as well as scientific questions that were explored in the classroom.

HW problem: Differential Gene Expression¶

While so far we have explored the data on a gene-by-gene basis, there are over 20,000 genes measured here! We would also like to have a more holistic view of how infection by COVID-19 impacts gene expression. To this end, we would like to reproduce the so-called volcano plot from Figure 4 of the paper, shown here:

The nature of a volcano plot is to assess which genes are likely to be differentially expressed between two conditions. Here, the authors are comparing the HealthyLungBiopsy sample to the COVID19Lung sample. The data points in red indicate that the gene expression changed by at least a factor 4 between the COVID and healthy lung and the difference is significant.

For this problem, try to recreate this volcano plot as faithfully as possible, and explore what some of these other differentially expressed genes (i.e. the authors only labeled a handful).

Note: I do **not** expect you to complete this in our hour session. There are a number of analysis decisions that come into play, so spend the rest of the time coming up with a plan of attack for this homework problem. Questions you may want to consider:

  • How will you compute fold change?
  • How will you compute a p-value? That is, what is the null hypothesis that you will be testing?
  • How will you adjust you p-values to address the issue of multiple testing?
  • How will you deal with counts of 0?

My own exploration¶

Everything below is my own exploration of the data in trying to recreate the volcano plot shown in Figure 4. This by no means what I would expect the students to create (especially not within an hour), but it is the type of material I would share with the students (via the course website) after having completed the exercise in class.

Let's dig in!

First, I'll make a lung-only dataframe that we will use for the rest of the analysis.

df_lung = df.loc[(df["treatment"]=="HealthyLungBiopsy") | (df["treatment"]=="COVID19Lung")]

Next, for each gene we will compute the fold change (expression in the COVID lung relative to the healthy lung) and the associated p value. At this point, I would emphasize a key aspect of reproducibility with respect to data analysis. Throughout the paper they mention "p-adjusted values" without specifying which test was done to compute a p-value, nor how the p-values were adjusted. Already, I am unable to reliably replicate their analysis due to lack of information. My best guess is that they conducted a two-sided t-test, as they would want to know whether a given gene was either up or down regulated and wouldn't assume a direction a priori. For now I compute a raw p-value, and will computed the adjusted p-values later. [Note this cell takes a while to run due to all the boolean indexing].

In [8]:
genes = df_lung["gene"].unique()
fold_changes = np.zeros(len(genes))
p_values = np.zeros(len(genes))

for i, gene in enumerate(genes):
                        
    # trim by gene first, so we only have to do this indexing once
    gene_df = df_lung.loc[(df_lung["gene"]==gene)]                 
           
    # get counts in the two treatments                      
    healthy_counts = gene_df.loc[gene_df["treatment"] == "HealthyLungBiopsy"]['count'].values
    covid_counts = gene_df.loc[gene_df["treatment"] == "COVID19Lung"]['count'].values
                          
    # compute fold change and p value
    fold_changes[i] = np.mean(covid_counts)/np.mean(healthy_counts)
    p_values[i] = stats.ttest_ind(healthy_counts, covid_counts)[1]

Next, to best emulate the figure, we will compute logs on the fold change and p-values. Since these values span orders of magnitude, it is best to plot them logarithmically to get a better sense of their distribution.

DGE_df["-log10 p-value"] = -np.log10(DGE_df["p-value"])

Now, we will adjust the p-values. Again I cannot be sure how they authors adjusted their p-values, and there are multiple ways to do so. This XKCD comic amusingly illustrates the issue of multiple testing, and the need to adjust the p-values when doing many tests subsequently, as is the case with the over 10,000 genes at play here. As a guess, I will do the Benjamini and Hochberg (BH) correction as described here, although I might be more partial to the more stringent Bonferoni correction. The first step of the BH correction is to sort the p-values, so we do that below:

In [12]:
DGE_df.sort_values(by="p-value", inplace=True)
DGE_df.head()

gene fold change p-value log2 fold change -log10 p-value

20634 MED22 0.003556 3.978837e-06 -8.135709 5.400244
3409 PRDM11 0.001815 6.611505e-06 -9.105909 5.179700
20312 CDC14B 0.001972 7.811310e-06 -8.985842 5.107276

Next, the p-values are multiplied by $m/k$, where $m$ is the number of tests being conducted (i.e. the number of genes) and $k$ is the position of the p-value in question in the ranked array. This amounts to lower (i.e. more significant) p-values being more heavily adjusted than higher p-values in an attempt to curb the False Discover Rate (FDR), which is another common name for this method.

In [13]:
DGE_df["BH adjusted p-value"] = DGE_df["p-value"] * len(DGE_df) / np.arange(1,len(DGE_df)+1)
DGE_df.head()

Finally, for aesthetic, we will wish to color the data by the extent of fold change as well as the significance. Below we determine the significance with 0.05 cutoff on our BH adjusted p-value, and consider a "large" change to be on greater than 4-fold (i.e. 2 on the log2 scale).

In [14]:
DGE_df["significance type"] = "TBD"

for index, row in DGE_df.iterrows():
    # boolean for significant or not
    sig = (row["BH adjusted p-value"] < 0.05)
    
    # first handle cases of fold change greater than 2
    if np.abs(row["log2 fold change"]) > 2:
        if sig:
            DGE_df.at[index, "significance type"] = "large change, significant"
        else:
            DGE_df.at[index, "significance type"] = "large change, not significant"
    
    # then handle all other cases, where fold change is less than 2 
    else:
        if sig:
            DGE_df.at[index, "significance type"] = "small change, significant"
        else:
            DGE_df.at[index, "significance type"] = "small change, not significant"

For me, this exercise illustrates the immense value of reproducibility in all aspects of our science, including data analysis. I am unable to recreate their plots not for lack of trying, but due to lack of transparency in the data analysis pipeline. The methods of this paper specify simply that ggplot was used to make the volcano plots, but they do not include any code. I suspect that the difference lies in me using raw counts rather than normalized counts, but I also cannot clearly determine how the normalization was done according to their methods. Throughout my teaching, I would emphasize the importance of sharing code publicly, to avoid pitfalls like this one. I have fortunately had fellow lab mates who are committed to such efforts, whose work serves as exemplar of what transparent data analysis should look like.
